<p>
 Then I headed to  one of the omnipresent comics stores to get some 
 <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manga">manga</a>.
 It turns out that there are various genres. Firstly, I can't read kanji yet,
 so I needed to get manga for children, say less than 13 years old,
 because there's the phonetic transcription 
 (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furigana">furigana</a>).
 These are roughly divided in those for girls and those for boys.
 I skimmed through some of the girlie ones and found way too much sugar for me.
 Moreover I know that it's hard to understand children, it's hard to understand
 the Japanese people, it's hard to understand the language
 and everybody knows it's hard to understand girls, therefore it would
 prove an impossible task to understand Japanese-written psychological stories of
 12 years old J-girls. 
 </p>
 
 <p>
 In the boys section I found lots of adventure manga; some of them
 you surely know (again, if you have a decent age) are: 
 <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_Ball">Dragon Ball</a>, 
 Yu-gi-ho, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hokuto_No_Ken">Hokuto no Ken</a> etc.
 I had to discard those because there's not much dialog and I'm sure 
 I won't find any occasion to yell "Ah! I did a delayed hit on your secret pressure point! 
 Now you only have seven seconds to live!". 
 In the end, I opted for 
 Japanese-written psichological stories of 12 years old J-<em>boys</em>.
</p>
